LOL rolled out of bed and took these so i look a mess but i wanted to do one last 2020 post! this year was obviously the worst and hard for all of us. but i don’t wanna dwell on the negativity. there are some things i’m very proud of myself for accomplishing this year. 
i finally came out this year after being confused most of my life and then terrified once i actually knew. 
i worked really hard on running and my fitness and lost over 30 lbs! i love running now and get so grumpy if i go too many days without a run lmao.
i finally released a new song (wonderland) after 3 years that i’m so proud of and that means so much to me for it’s about my struggle with coming out.
and lastly i’ve found a love for streaming!! i’ve always wanted to give it a shot but i had so much anxiety to do it but i’ve finally overcome it and it’s been so fun so far :-) 
so this year was horrible and i’ve definitely got some work to do with my mental health, but i’m at least proud of myself for these things and i’m ready to continue working on improving myself in 2021

what are you proud of yourself for this year?

So yesterday we flew a helicopter to a remote glacier and ice climbed up it and it was without a doubt one of the hardest things I’ve ever done, physically yes but mainly mentally. I have a really bad fear of heights when i don’t feel secure - like i can do airplanes and roller coasters just fine bc im strapped and safe. But like being on cliffs or looking over balcony’s, etc - anything where there’s a chance i can fall, I’m terrified of and my anxiety gets just about unbearable. We had a harness but i couldn’t help how anxious i still got. I knew I’d get freaked out but i reacted worse than i thought and almost had a panic attack several times LOOOL but what I’m so proud of is my body went into full on adrenaline and badass mode. I zipped up the ice cliff we climbed up SO fast without a struggle, didn’t fall once and completely crushed it. I could feel how strong my body was and could feel my muscles just taking over and doing their thing like it was just another day at the gym. Not sure where I’m going with this but I’m just SO proud of myself and my body bc i completely pushed myself to the limits today and I’ve always been worried in those situations that i would just freeze and not be able to move but today i learned that in tough situations my body reacts in a positive way and pushes through 😎 thanks @eltoncastee for testing my limits haha i love to challenge myself and that was one of the biggest ever for me
I’m currently thriving in alaska bc im not sweating 24/7 for once 😎 also it’s fake fur don’t worry

this year was filled with regrets to be honest. i lost myself in so many different ways. i felt like i wasted so much time. it was not until this last month i realized how sorry I was to my younger self. i felt like i wasted so much of her time. 

It was also not until the last few months that I remember what my younger self even looked like. I don’t look thru photo albums often so I don’t remember what she looked like. However when I saw a picture of her, I was so happy. She’s so cute. But i almost couldn’t recognize her because there is no way that naive little girl is actually me. but the truth is, she was once me. and i felt so protective of her. 

she is my current lock screen right now. I use it to remind myself that I need to be kinder to myself. I need to do things for her and make it up to her. it’s still a bit hard to get use to but i’m trying.

I believe 2023 is going to be a turning point for all of us. I hope we can all achieve the most this year. i want to be different this year. for past years i never looked forward to new years. i didnt like creating new years goals because I feel like they just set me up for disappointments but this past month I feel different. I wrote down goals and for some reason, I sincerely believe I can achieve this. 

I often don’t like taking myself seriously and i think it’s mainly bc i don’t wanna face the disappointments. but if i don’t take myself seriously, who will????? so yes, let’s all start taking ourselves seriously and write down crazy goals because WHY TF NOT????? 

I will be shameless, delusional and cringe this 2023 😗😗💋💋🫦🫦♥️♥️💞 (as if i haven’t done that enough)

Thank you for being here ♥️

I’ll see you all next year 🌟

In memory of Doomsday💛⚠️🐷⭐️Feeling sad but also grateful. These are the merch items that were supposed to come out 2 years ago with the Doomsday Palette release. I never thought we were going to put them out but Mark at Killer Merch ordered some as a little memorial for the series and the palette. Looking at the pig mask idea and the Doomsday logo used to make me cry but now it makes me happy because it reminds me of this series which I’m so proud of. No pressure to get any of this merch but if you wanna rep the collection that we loved so much you can check it out in my bio💛

I can’t believe the series is over. I can’t put into words what this experience has meant to me and what it has done for my life. I used to look at the conspiracy palette and cry because it symbolised the beginning of a very tough time for me and now I can hold it again and remember all the love and joy it brought. Thank you guys for all the beautiful and meaningful comments you left on the finale. I cried last night reading them and it reminded me why I love making series. It just felt like I found my purpose again. Thank you :,))) Thank you Jeffree for being one of the main people in my life who I can count on and who brings out the creativity in me. I love you so much and I can’t put into words how proud I am of you. Thank you Ryland for being my rock and for bringing a voice of reason and understanding. Thank you Chris for being such a talent friend and for getting me excited about making things again. And thank you Youtube for supporting the series and trending the episodes. I’m so grateful to be making stuff like this. I hope you enjoyed the series and I can’t wait to make another one. ❤️

what a year it’s been. never did i ever imagine my journey would include going to rehab… multiple times. but i’m thankful i found the courage and bravery to do so. this last year includes a lot of other things but i want to focus on my journey of getting sober. it was so fucking scary to admit that i needed rehab and that this “issue” wasn’t something i could fix on my own. i’m so thankful that i dug deep and found the courage and bravery to commit to a program and see it through, everytime i went. i knew nothing about rehab, or what i was signing up for. but i was met with the kindest, most understanding strangers who are now life long friends. to be surrounded by people who you don’t know at all, yet understand such a deep and scary part of yourself because they too live it was so healing. i want to dedicate my “end of the year” post to everyone still struggling in silence. i hope you know that you don’t have to live that way. there is a way out, and it’s a lot less scary than your brain is convincing you it is. it’s not easy, but it’s worth it. thank you for sticking by me, encouraging me, and believing in me. i’m no where near where i want to be in my sobriety, but everyday i get the chance to get closer, and i’d choose that over spending another day blacked out at 10am everytime. we do heal. we do recover. and best of all, we have each other to lean on. i love you 🥺♥️

You’re lookin at a girl who just completed her 3 week inpatient rehab stay! I think when I first arrived I was still in a bit of denial that I actually needed to be there. And that’s okay, all that matters is that I showed up and stayed. And the longer I stayed, the most obvious it became that I was exactly where I needed to be. I am so grateful for all the people I met and became family with. I have learned so much about myself, and began to truly heal the parts of me that I had been trying to numb for so many years. One of our assignments was to write a goodbye letter to alcohol. I decided I wanted to share it with you all. I was nervous to publicly talk about going to rehab but the support you all have shown has been such a source of strength and motivation on the days where it’s a bit harder to stick it out. If you’re struggling I hope that you know you’re not alone. And there is light at the end of the tunnel. I love you. Thank you 🤍

after 17 beautiful days at home with family, i have decided to fly back to california and enter rehab. i’ve always been honest and transparent about my mental health, but have held my struggle with addiction close to my chest. i deserve better than the version of myself that i’ve been and i’m finally putting healing first. i love you all and can’t put into words how much of an impact all of your comments and messages truly have and how much they keep me pushing forward. i never thought this would be my life. but i’m here now and it’s never too late to change. thank you for always believing in me, even when i no longer do. see you soon. ♥️

This year I watched the light come back into my eyes after a couple years of feeling like it never would. I’m ending this year feeling proud of myself for not giving up but instead, finding whatever bit of positivity there was in some of the hardest and most painful situations. It feels like I’ve spent years powering through and being determined not to give up on myself and only now have I taken a second to turn around and look back at all the the moments of strength and compassion I showed myself. I have learned that you have to be your biggest cheerleader. You have to believe that you deserve happiness. Because you do. I hope you all enter 2023 knowing just how strong you are. And if you don’t quite believe in yourself yet, I do! :) See you next yearrrrrr 🥹🫶🏼

Bedroom ✅ 
This room is in a mezzanine level with not much natural light reaching from the living room, so I wanted to create an inviting, cosy and almost cabin-like space to be in. I sketched out (poorly) my idea so that Felix could build the wooden wall and shelving to frame the bed; we removed the carpet and installed wood floors, and opted for a platform bed. This room is long and has no natural light; it used to have chrome splashbacks, off white walls and beige cupboards. With its black cabinetry and oversized island, @lizakoshy’s Los Angeles kitchen, which was designed by Tyka Pryde Edwards (@tykapryde), is certainly contemporary in style. But around the holidays, the actor and host, who first gained popularity on the now defunct social media platform Vine and parlayed that into a successful career on YouTube, as well as traditional film and TV, is all about leaning into cozy traditions. “I asked Tyka for an elegant spice cabinet aesthetic,” explains Koshy. “You’ve got your cumin. You’ve got your paprika. It’s 50 shades of brown in here, but everything just feels so warm and cozy and inviting.”

See how she gets ready for the holidays in a new video at the link in our bio.

last month i visited Jordan with UNHCR, the UN Refugee Agency (@refugees). the lovely families i met with were forced to flee their homes in Syria nearly 12 years ago now.

moms like Dania, who’s had her world flipped upside down & remains hopeful to give her son the world & safe home he deserves. geniuses like 17-year-old Rania who helped invent robotic shoes to help visually impaired people walk in her community at Zaatari Refugee Camp. or youth empowering groups like TIGER who support young refugee students by strengthening their sense of identity & creativity by learning new skills & sharing their art & conversation in a safe space w/ one another. 

refugees have their stories to share & i’ve now seen first-hand how UNHCR is always there to support them in those journeys. scroll down my page to be introduced to the genius that is Rania. follow @refugees to hear more about the trip over the coming week.

© UNHCR/Caroline Irby

Imagine being 17 and claiming the title of robotics whizz, inventor, a gold medal runner, a journalist, and beyond. 
 
All accomplished while living life in Zaatari Refugee Camp in Jordan after your family was forced to flee Syria over a decade ago. That’s what Rania here has done, all with hope and humility. We’re in awe of her pure potential.
 
It’s on all of us to amplify and support stories like Rania’s to make sure she has a well-deserved shot at achieving her dreams. The spotlight belongs to her today.
 
#jordan #zaatari

History belongs to the heroes. But to get the full story, sometimes you have to ask the side characters.

The lives of Leonardo da Vinci, Henry VIII and Queen Victoria fill bookshelves and fascinate scholars all over the world. But little attention is given to the ferret who posed for the renaissance master, the servant who oversaw the Tudor’s toilet time, or the famous horse who thrilled the miserable old monarch.

These supporting cast members have been waiting in the wings for too long, and Adrian Bliss thinks it’s high time they join their glory-hogging contemporaries in the spotlight. Fortunately, - thanks to some recently discovered ancient complaint letters, court transcripts and memoirs in bottles - now they can.

Equal parts fascinating and hilarious, the Greatest Nobodies of History is a surreal love letter to life’s forgotten heroes featuring hitherto undocumented accounts from Ancient Greece to the frontlines of the Great Emu War.

All that follows really happened, and some of it could even be true

Oh sweet, sweet day six with your forever satirical practice intros. Ten years ago I did this day six intro because it was absurd how all the core training videos were truly obsessed with six pack abs. The catch was that these practices are anything but what those videos claim to be and the opposite of what they do for one’s anatomy and soul. 

A fresh new day 6 launched today in the 30 day series! Join me for an 18 minute, core centering session designed to help you connect to the full spectrum of your core muscles holistically, as well focus the mind for optimal mental health.
 
Check in with your center.

The physical branch of yoga offers us the chance to better understand and get to know ourselves.

Day six is my favorite. Who said core work had to be a hard hot mess? I love this approach. It’s efficient and impactful and leaves your nervous system feeling cared for. 

Core work for the win. Do you trust me?

Though we need to weep your loss, 
You dwell in that safe place in our hearts, 
Where no storm or night or pain can reach you. 

Your love was like the dawn 
Brightening over our lives 
Awakening beneath the dark 
A further adventure of colour. 

The sound of your voice 
Found for us 
A new music 
That brightened everything. 

Whatever you enfolded in your gaze 
Quickened in the joy of its being; 
You placed smiles like flowers 
On the altar of the heart. 
Your mind always sparkled 
With wonder at things. 

Though your days here were brief, 
Your spirit was live, awake, complete. 

We look towards each other no longer 
From the old distance of our names; 
Now you dwell inside the rhythm of breath, 
As close to us as we are to ourselves. 

Though we cannot see you with outward eyes,
We know our soul's gaze is upon your face, 
Smiling back at us from within everything 
To which we bring our best refinement. 

Let us not look for you only in memory, 
Where we would grow lonely without you. 
You would want us to find you in presence, 
Beside us when beauty brightens, 
When kindness glows 
And music echoes eternal tones. 

When orchids brighten the earth, 
Darkest winter has turned to spring; 
May this dark grief flower with hope 
In every heart that loves you. 

May you continue to inspire us: 

To enter each day with a generous heart. 
To serve the call of courage and love 
Until we see your beautiful face again 
In that land where there is no more separation, 
Where all tears will be wiped from our mind, 
And where we will never lose you again.

John O'Donohue
✨

It’s been over a year and this is still one of my favourite experiences that I’ve ever had ✨

This was the week I overcame so many fears & limiting beliefs which resulted in me deciding to leave Barcelona to travel for a year. This was also the week that I finally started to really understand what my vision for the future was, and decided that I will get my yoga teaching certification to get closer to that. Before this trip I was EXTREMELY lost on what I wanted to do (you can even see it in my videos of Jan 2023😂). 

I’m forever grateful for every single person I met there - you all changed my life 🫶🏼🥹

(Wim resting his hand on my head in the last slide is a core memory 😂)

Here are some of the cool things we did:
- Almost 2 hours total of breathwork every day
- Jumped off a 7m cliff into ice cold water
- Hiked in shorts for 5 hours up an icy mountain
- Walked barefoot in the snow for almost an hour straight
- Spent 10 minutes straight in an almost frozen river
- & a loooot of time in the sauna 🌤️

Would you ever consider doing something like this?

best decision I ever made 🥹

#travel #digitalnomad #travelgram #gapyear

Where I’ve worked from since I became a digital nomad last year ✨🧳

📍Sicily, Italy (May):
I moved to a super remote area and lived here for just over a month. It was a little too remote 🥲 and I started feeling quite lonely because the town I lived in was half empty.

📍Rome, Italy (Jun):
I wasn’t ready to leave Italy just yet, but after my quiet month in Sicily, I craved the energy of a city. This trip made me realise that while I had always considered moving to Rome long-term, it wasn’t the best fit for me.

📍Dunshaughlin, Ireland (Jul):
I stayed with family in Ireland for a couple of weeks between trips. I’m glad I got to spend some time here before they moved out the following month. I spent 10 years of my life living in that little village and I probably won’t be back for years 😢

📍Riga, Latvia (Aug):
Then, I decided to move to my birth town for a month! I left Latvia when I was 8, and had never experienced living there in my own apartment. I looooved it 🥹 & inner child was so happy to finally live in the same country as my dad again.

📍Alicante, Spain (Sep):
I spent almost a whole month here because I was helping my mom and brother move from Ireland. I became the official Spanish translator for the move 🤩 Since my mom works remotely too, we worked a lot together.

📍Uluwatu, Bali (Oct-Nov):
My first-ever experience of living in Bali! I fell in love with the island and its people. I spent two months here, working and becoming a certified yoga teacher.

📍Canggu, Bali (Dec-Jan):
After two months in a beach town, I was ready for a change of pace, so I moved an hour north to a super busy area of Bali, known as the "city of digital nomads."🤩

📍Rio de Janeiro, Brazil (Jan):
Although I was only here for a week, I had full intentions of staying for three months. I’m keeping this on my list because I still want to come back and spend a longer time here.

📍Barcelona, Spain (Feb):
Back in my casita <3 Not sure how long I’m here for, but for now, this is the best place for me to be :)

I’m curious, what country would you love to experience living in eventually?🌎

I moved to Barcelona exactly 3 months ago 🥹🫶🏼 

here are some little observations and changes that I’ve noticed in my life in that time

⚡️I LOVE the communication style of Spanish people
Spanish people speak very openly and directly in comparison to any of the other countries I’ve lived in and I LOVE it. Also they’re very affectionate people and a lot more comfortable with physical touch (a lot of hugging, kissing on the cheek when first meeting someone, and a loot of PDA in comparison to Ireland/UK)

⚡️people work to live, not live to work
I’m mostly comparing Barcelona to London in this point but you can really notice a big difference in the work/life balance. People walk slower, eat slower and in general just seem more relaxed and at peace <3 

⚡️I realised I didn’t know as much Spanish as I think I knew
I really feel like I’m relearning the whole language to some point and no matter how much I studied I couldn’t have been fully prepared. The Spanish being spoken around me has colloquial phrases (that I’ve never heard before) for almost everything. But I kind of love it - I still have so much to learn.

 ⚡️living alone can be so lonely
I love when it’s quiet at home but not that quiet 😵‍💫 There’s been so many times that I’ve invited people to my house or went out just because I didn’t want to be home alone again.

⚡️my surroundings have way too much power over me
I cannot explain how much happier I’ve gotten since I moved to Spain and that almost worries me that I’m relying a little too much on external factors like weather to keep me happy... 

⚡️family is everything 
Obviously I’m always extremely grateful for my family but having my cousin here during this moving process has changed everything. The amount of times she has helped me with so many stressful processes (she has literally gone to the bank with me every day for the last 3 days) 🥹 Also having your best friend live so close to you is a big plus. @klaudialenkovska you’re my favourite person, thank you for existing tqm <3

overall, moving here has been the best decision ever and I’m forever grateful to be living in such a beautiful country surrounded by the best people <3

Lisbon surprised me in the best way 🥹
and now I’m 100% positive I’ll want to live here for at least a couple of months in the future ❤️

Bruh, kiss a potato and tango with a microwave bc we about to make potato chips with a microwave! 🥔🔥

I was shocked by how easy this was! All you need is a potato and microwave. This method presents a healthier option too as it’s not cooked in any oil. AND the crisp is out of this world.

The goods - large potato, mandoline/other slicer/knife, salt and pepper, bowl of ice and water

The moves - rinse your potato, peel (optional), and slice as thin as possible using a mandoline or knife, preferable less than 1/16” in thickness. Throw slices in the ice bath for 15 minutes, bring them out and pat them as dry as possible. Lay them on a dish of parchment paper, coating each side with salt and pepper (or whatever spice you want). No need for oil! Then throw the plate in the microwave on high for 5 minutes, bring them out, flip onto other side, throw back in microwave for 5 more minutes, bring out, let it sit for 2 minutes, and enjoy!!

Please please be careful if you’re using a mandoline, I may or may not have hurt myself while making this vid. Safety first fam! 

Also obvious but pro tip: the thinner the crispier, the fatter the potato-ier

Had the honor of trying these $128 crown melons from @ikigai_fruits and fam they are no joke!

Some of the best muskmelon you can find, these crown melons are only grown specially in the western region of the Shizuoka Prefecture in Japan, and you can tell by the taste that they put mastery and love into making them perfect. The juice and flavor each bite packs is wild, and the slurp factor is next level. If you ever have the chance or want to snag, you should definitely try. Easily the juiciest melon I’ve ever had! 🍈🤯🔥

Would you try these? What fruit have you always wanted to try the rare/expensive/mastered version of?

It’s been raining heavy in LA so I had to whip up some shabu shabu to keep me warm. 🍲🔥✨

Something about broth heating up my soul and the ability to eat any and all of my favorite veggies and meats to my desired texture and cookedness is just beautiful uknowwhatimean? 

The goods - carrots, bok choy, cabbage, mushrooms (the more the variety the better imo! My favorite for shabu specifically is enoki), tofu, shabu meat (in Asian markets they will typically label as “good for shabu/soup”), water, konbu (dried kelp), anchovy stock powder, sesame sauce, ponzu

The moves - cut up all veggies to desired lengths and sizes, create dashi stock by boiling 3 cups of water and immersing the konbu and fish stock powder for 5-10 minutes (the longer you leave it the stronger the taste and less water due to evaporation), then add veggies into the stock as well as meat, let dance with the soup and cook, and then enjoy with ponzu and sesame sauce.

bruh, idk why i thought chicken skewers were so intimidating to make but they are super easy, fun, and extra juicy, especially in an air fryer. I might be a skewer boy for life fam no lie 👀😮‍💨🔥

the goods - boneless skinless chicken thighs cut into 1 inch pieces, salt, black pepper, garlic, lemon zest, paprika, olive oil. for the lemon pepper butter - 1/2 stick unsalted butter partially melted, salt, black pepper, lemon zest, paprika, pinch of sugar, lemon juice

the moves - in a bowl add in the chicken thighs, salt, black pepper, minced garlic, lemon zest, paprika and olive oil, and mix until everything has danced and thoroughly combined with each other. skewer your marinated chicken thighs onto each skewer tightly. set all your skewered meat into air fryer for 12 mins at 400F for 10-15 min. flip/rotate the skewers and air fry at 400F for another 10 minutes or until the internal temperature reaches 165F.

for the lemon pepper butter, add in and mix unsalted butter, salt, black pepper, lemon zest, paprika, sugar, lemon juice into bowl. once skewers are cooked, baste with this butter, serve immediately, and welcome to slurp city.

this spicy tuna crispy rice is about to make you the talk of the town fam 😮‍💨🔥

the goods - white rice, sushi grade tuna, sriracha, kewpie mayo, soy sauce, sesame oil,  avocado, green onions, vegetable oil, good vibes

the moves - cook a cup of white rice and place into a small square container or baking tray lined with plastic wrap. pat into a nice 1/2 inch thiccc square block and put in fridge for 30 min - 1 hour, which will help it solidify and easier to cut into cubes later. next, prep the spicy tuna by cutting up the raw tuna to your desired chunkiness. add to bowl with sriracha, kewpie mayo, soy sauce, sesame oil, and mix. take the rice out of fridge and slice into inch rectangle bites. in a skillet, heat vegetable oil until hot, and gently place each rice piece into the pan. rotate on all sides until crispy brown. be careful of the oil please! finally we assemble by adding thinly sliced avo pieces on top of the crispy rice, along with your spicy tuna and garnished with green onions. enjoy!

김밥 (kimbap) aka Korean seaweed rice rolls is one of my favorite foods and always reminds me of my childhood and family. while the beauty of these is that you can put in whatever you’d like, this is how momma choi made it for us growing up and to this day.

crispy salmon bites with a kick? yes please!

the marinated salmon in itself is amazing, but when coupled with avocado and jalapeño and served in a crispy rice paper wrap, we on a new level fam. also I learned that my rice paper wrapping skills def needs some work haha

the goods - salmon, salt, paprika, garlic, low sodium soy sauce, brown sugar, red pepper flakes, sriracha, avocado, jalapeno or serrano, rice paper, good vibes

the moves - cut salmon into 1-inch cubes, prep the salmon marinade by putting in a bowl and mixing the garlic, soy sauce, paprika, salt, brown sugar, red pepper flakes, and sriracha. put sauce over salmon, toss, and let marinate for 3-4 hours. in a pan on medium heat, fry salmon on each side until golden brown. dip rice paper in water, add the salmon cube, avocado, and jalapeño and wrap em up. add to pan w some olive oil and fry bites evenly on each side. enjoy!

sashimi/sushi from frozen salmon? say less.

I’ve been dying to try this and can confidently say I am a Costco salmon sashimi boy for life now haha. affordable, easy, delicious. shouts to the sushi guy for this hack!

the goods - frozen farm raised salmon from costco, 4 cups water, 2 tablespoons of salt, bowl, good vibes

the moves - in a bowl add 4 cups water and 2 tablespoons of salt (go for around 3-4% here) and submerge the frozen salmon. put in fridge for 30 minutes. bring bad boy out and pat dry. you can eat it at this point but it’s recommended to put in fridge for 3-5 hours for firmness and taste. after 3-5 hours, remove from fridge, pat dry again, slice, and enjoy!

according to the sushi guy, the FDA says that raw seafood must be frozen for 7 days. Costco frozen farmed salmon is exempt from this rule due to their parasite-free feed. they are also flash frozen immediately. there’s always some bacterial risk with eating raw or undercooked fish but from a parasite perspective it should be safe. I’m def no pro and encourage those who are wary to take precautions or do research before trying. happy eating!

Things we learnt on our day in Tokyo.. 
Toby wore black jeans and regretted it. Hot. 
I’m finding it hard to say no to the clothes. The trees are magical and look like they can talk. It wouldn’t surprise me if you told me they can. The food is literally bursting at the seams with flavour. All I need for breakfast, lunch and dinner is dumplings. 
The fruit here doesn’t taste like fruit, it’s fruit squared. If I could hand deliver a single grape (oh my god the grapes here 😱) to everyone I would but I can’t and they’ll probably squish in the travel. 
I need another suitcase because I can’t leave things behind at the stalls. 
I packed wrong. High waisted jean shorts- nope. Next time= more floaty floaty things.
The people here are the kindest and the purest. I want to cuddle everyone but I won’t because even though they’re kind I’m also a stranger. 
If there’s a gap in the buildings, you know they’ll build a cute adorable Polly pocket building that fits perfectly. 
I want to bathe in noodles. 
We cooked some hearts and some cocks and called it a night. 

Jet lag. Is. A. Bitch. Nothing a grape can’t fix.

Fun fact about these shots outside, we were in the middle of setting up and shooting THAT scene at the end with Nathan and Allison sat opposite each other on a round table (no spoilers don’t worry) and one of the cameras wouldn’t work. I can’t seem to remember why but it was full on ‘oh shit oh no we don’t have much time oh fuck’ energy going on. And Zach got his Red Komodo camera out and said let’s just shoot some content outside in the beautiful red leaves and we did. Whilst the other camera was being tinkered with. 
For me, I’ve always loved the thrill of having to turn the day around and change everything ‘right now’. It happens a lot on smaller movies due to not wanting to waste any of the shoot day because of budget, everyone just having to turn the day on it’s head instantly in that moment because you don’t have time to dawdle. That energy of, if you don’t move now we will lose this day and this time so let’s just shoot something. 
At the beginning of my career I learnt only on tiny baby iddy indie movies, that just HAD to have that energy throughout or else you came out with nothing. 
I love it. I love that magic on a film set. Everyone moving fast, everyone dedicated, moving lights and sandbags and booms and radio’s last minute getting everything out of shot. It weirdly, nearly always captures something pure magic. 
This shot was magic!

It’s been a pleasure to watch this grow, and now it’s all up to you- audience! 
Nearly. This Friday. 
Enjoy.. for now, here’s some wonderful snippets from our time together.
@agoodpersonmov

Whaaaaaaat? A week? Guys, I can’t believe you get to see this in a week. 
Slowly but surely more and more people have been seeing our baby in small screenings in the UK and US, it’s shit scary and bloody exciting all in the same breath but unbelievably rewarding when we hear what you’ve had to say. 
Put it in your calendar… it’s nearly time to watch A Good Person. @agoodpersonmov

He followed me around with his phone taking pictures of every angle. Video to come… 
I love the fun that explodes from his gowns, it truly is playing the best dress up my 6 year old self could possibly imagine. 

So happy to have these moments captured by @gregwilliamsphotography, always a pleasure prancing and blowing kisses in a garden.

we’ve been squealing and sharing moments for the last two days. 
An actual dream supporting my friend and unbelievably talented designer @harris_reed. Wearing your clothes is like being given the best key to the best dress up box there is. 
It’s full and alive and full to the brim with love. Thank you my darling for including me and such a massive well done for all that you’ve made and achieved! 
#alltheworldsastage
Photo shared by Florence Pugh on February 14, 2023 tagging @pussinboots.

It’s our Missy moo’s birthday today! 
We fostered her three years ago and fell in love with her on day one so asked to adopt. 
She is the LIGHT OF MY LIFE. I’ve never walked with someone who gets more smiles just walking down the street than she does. 
She snuggles me when I’m sad and sings opera when I come home. Even makeup artists are jealous of her natural eye shadow look. 
This dog.. she makes my heart happy.

AND… ‘Puss in Boots The Last Wish’ has also been nominated for a BAFTA!!! 
What a night this will be to celebrate. So glad this movie is getting the recognition it deserves, fantastic storyline with brilliant creators at its core. 

Perfect timing as well- it comes out in UK cinemas on February 3rd! 
Yipppeeee.

Well that was beautiful. 
The 3rd of Jan is always so crap as no one wants to do anything but splodge and nurse their NYE hangover. Every year I’m astonished friends want to do anything! I’m so unbelievably grateful to all of you who came, it’s always a surprise! Beautiful people, beautiful way to start the year, beautiful day. 
Thank you to all of you who wished me well on my special day. I received them all and send kisses right back. 
Thank you @thestandardlondon for hosting such a fabtastic night. @elli1276 you really went above and beyond to make it so special and I am so so thankful.

Dripping with Valentino red from shoulders to beyond, a design by the man himself. Quite the pinch me moment. 
We danced, we cheers’ed, we hugged. Glorious evening.
@maisonvalentino

It’s how I started and where I feel at home, thank you so much for having us and to all those nominated AND those who won- CONGRATULATIONS.

That's a wrap! My days on Ungentlemanly Warfare are over. Tis a sad day. I'm going to echo the sentiments of my co-stars and sing the praises of our intrepid crew. It's rare to come across a team so driven, dedicated and committed to the storytelling. That drive and dedication is only intensified by having a leader such as Guy Ritchie. His ability to weave story and create character might be second to none, and he wields it like it were magic. 

Those ingredients - skill, drive, and exceptional talent at the top, are only three of the ingredients needed for an experience that will last forever in memory. The fourth is happiness. Guy creates happiness on his set, it's a joyful place to be, full of laughter and japes and jests. The crew and cast's approach and personality is key in this. Everyone,  without fail, was able to enjoy themselves while also working hard and being exceptional. 

This wee pontification would not be complete without heaping praise upon my fellow actors. Alan Ritchson, the man mountain, with a heart of gold, and a wisdom and talent that can sweep you off your feet. Alex Pettyfer, the lover, the laugher, the warmth of a big smile and a jaw line that would challenge the Turkish mountains. Henry Golding Jnr, a snap quick acting reaction time, handsome beyond belief and always a man I was happy to see. And the last (but not the least) of my immediate team of misfits, Hero Fiennes Tiffin - a mega star in the making. I know a lot of you know him already, but my oh my he's going to have a magnificent career. 

To the makers of The Ministry of Ungentlemanly Warfare I shall miss you all, and gods willing - see you soon.

Happy International Men's Day, gents! Thank you for all that you do for us, and for your families. How are you all doing? Worth asking ourselves that from time to time, and definitely worth asking other men too. 

I figured it being International Men's Day that I should introduce you to my first brisket! Was a touch nervous going into this one, but it turned out surprisingly well!

....cooking details incoming....

Pulled the brisket (Snake River Farms) from defrosting in the fridge. Trimmed the brisket with a frustratingly dull (and small) knife, and seasoned it with a black rub called "Hardcore Carnivore, Black, Beef Seasoning." I then put it back in the fridge for 48 hours.

Smoked the brisket with a pellet smoker (Yoder ys640) using Hickory and Mesquite pellets 50/50. 

Cooking started on Friday evening at 225F for a few hours, and I soon realised that it was cooking waaay too quickly, so I dropped temp down to 180 overnight. In the AM I got up and readjusted the smoker to 225F until the brisket temps hit the "stall" at 165-170F (depending on which temp probe I was reading!) I then wrapped it in butcher paper and turned the temp up to 250F on the smoker until the brisket was done at 205F (which also happened fairly quickly). Total cook time 17 hours 30mins

I let it rest in the cooler for an hour and a half wrapped in an old towel. 

Then sliced and served....had to resist squeezing the brisket. I've seen enough redditors get crucified for that.....didn't want to meet my end after my first brisket! I assure you though, it was juicy as fcark! 

I haven't had much brisket in my time, but Natalie (my lovely lady) is from Texas and it got her vote of approval (which I'm hoping wasn't biased!). I've got loads to learn yet, but it was pretty tasty for a first go.

I should also mention that I'm not in business with any of the companies I mentioned above! Just giving credit where it's due for good products.

Once again, Happy International Men's Day, fellas.

#InternationalMensDay

There is a good chance that some wines were drank along with said foods. What you see above are Joojeh kababs (Persian style chicken kebabs), some gyro bread, saffron rice, and Tzatziki, all made from scratch. Different years, different gears, and even a superteam slaying moustache! All during the Durrell Challenge. Which, once again, fast approaches.

For those not in the know, The Durrell Wildlife Conservation Trust is a charity that focuses on saving animal species that are on the brink of extinction. And you lucky folks have the opportunity to help out said, adorable, nigh extinct little beasties by running The Challenge and raising some always appreciated funds for them!

You can take part virtually or go to Jersey in person and visit the famous Jersey Zoo itself! It's a 13km run and it will take place on Sunday 22 May in Jersey or, if you are running it virtually you can do so from Friday 20 May to Monday 23 May.

I finally made the pilgrimage to Warhammer World, and what a day I had! I don't often get giddy with excitement, but getting to meet the likes of Andy Smillie, Mark Chambers, Wade Pryce, and Aiden Daly and being able to pick their brains about minute and elusive parts of the lore, while wandering the halls of the exhibition centre was a dream come true. 

Some of you may not know what Warhammer is, and i urge you to take a look. If you live in the UK definitely go to Warhammer World. The artistry involved and the synergy between miniature designs that are so enormously diverse, is extraordinary. The brilliance of the artistry is rather wonderfully matched, by the sense of community and also the passion that is shown by both the people who work there and the people who visit. I don't often feel at home, but I did that day. 

#WarhammerCommunity

All I can say is please keep spreading love in this world 🫶 happy 2024 !!! love u all 🐉🧧🎊

A glimpse into my parents’ humble beginnings.. This post is dedicated to the beautiful souls of Vietnam who do incredibly backbreaking work to feed their families. Much like these hardworking people, my parents weren’t born into generational wealth. Learning more about their journey, I can’t help but feel like what I do is nothing compared to what these individuals endure every day for what is considered a few dollars in America, and yet, they pour their hearts into each encounter and express immense gratitude. I am constantly in tears and awe at the great lengths they do to survive. From children to the elderly, the collective effort to work under excruciating circumstances in order to support their family is the most admirable, selfless act that I had the honor to witness firsthand. 

It’s been 17 years since I’ve come back to Vietnam. Now as an adult, I finally have the capacity to understand the hard truths and see life clearly. This is being written by probably the laziest and most privileged person of my ancestry (I don’t mean to discredit what I do. Just making fun of myself while knowing there is some truth to it). To everyone here, America is a dream. Growing up in America myself, my eyes are open to the life I’ve taken for granted and my silly first world problems no longer feel relevant. The veil of separation has finally been lifted and I can truly cherish and commemorate my family’s origins 🥺🇻🇳🙏❤️

Thoughts from visiting ancient Vietnamese villages, battlegrounds, and temples honoring warriors & scholars: I am remembering the rich history of our wars and spiritual sanctuaries. Places I’ve wanderlust my entire life to see. Never been here before in this lifetime, but somehow, my soul felt like it was returning home. Standing close to the statues of the past, I can’t help but feel a sense of recognition as if I’m looking at remnants of myself from long ago. My body has a deep, visceral reaction just from being here. A reaction this intense can only come from an unconscious, intuitive place that I, in this existence, cannot even comprehend. Witnessing such beautiful landmarks, I find myself thinking.. Is it possible I’ve had a past life here before and came back to pursue my wildest dreams and passions as the very first American born Vietnamese woman in my entire ancestry? Everything about this trip so far has felt so divinely inspired, as if we are being gently guided by the hands of our ancestors. Pure moments of synchronicity that literally make me drop to my knees, bowing down to the magnificent power the universe has blessed our trip with. I’ve felt such overwhelming gratitude. All I can say is that life is so mysterious and I know next to nothing about it. I am truly lucky to be able to experience the ever-expansive magic that surrounds us all.

I love sharing the remarkable sights of Vietnam, but I want to talk about how the people here have changed me. Traveling around Vietnam, I have spent hours quietly crying to myself, heartbroken at how privileged I am. The standard of living in Vietnam is no where near as luxurious as America, but their spirit and kindness is so strongly felt in my heart. I want to honor the people here and offer new perspective while doing it in the most respectful way. This trip has ignited even more purpose in my soul. I will forever write love letters to Vietnam and express its spirit through my art and everything I do. I am so beyond grateful to be connected to such a beautiful country and the most humble, hard working people who embody the deepest humility I’ve ever experienced 🫶🇻🇳🪷

The poor with smiles on their faces and gracious hearts will teach you so much more than the privileged who don’t appreciate what they have.

Give the women in your life their flowers now 🌹🌻🌷😤 The biggest props to the women in my life who have uplifted me and changed my life for the better. 2022 would’ve sucked without you. So deeply grateful for the years of love and friendship we’ve shared together. Through all the tears and laughter, you have made life so much more worth living. Cheers to you, my loves 🥂💖 I will never stop celebrating the beauty, complexity, and humanity of you.
